### Session 3 — GPU Acceleration

#### Problem: PyTorch installed as CPU-only

**Symptom:**
```
[ReID] CUDA requested but not available; using CPU
```
Pipeline ran at only **~2.5 FPS**.

**Root cause:** PyTorch was installed as `torch==2.11.0+cpu` — a CPU-only build. The RTX 3050 GPU was completely unused.

**Verification:**
```bash
python -c "import torch; print(torch.__version__)"
# 2.11.0+cpu   ← no CUDA support
nvidia-smi
# NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3050 Laptop GPU | Driver 595.97 | CUDA 13.2
```

**Fix:**
```bash
pip install torch torchvision \
    --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu124 \
    --force-reinstall --no-deps
```

**Result:**
```
[ReID] OSNet loaded on cuda        ← GPU active
[main] pipeline-fps=7.9            ← was 2.5 FPS, now 7.9 FPS (3× speedup)
```

> **Why `cu124` and not `cu132`?** PyTorch CUDA wheels are built against specific CUDA toolkit versions. The highest available stable wheel for Python 3.13 at time of install was `cu124` (CUDA 12.4). NVIDIA driver 595.97 is forward-compatible — it can run CUDA 12.4 code despite reporting CUDA 13.2.

